  "prompt": "Why does Obama say ISIL instead of ISIS?",
  "response": "President Obama and others in his administration have often used the term \"ISIL\" (Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant) instead of \"ISIS\" (Islamic State of Iraq and Syria) primarily for linguistic and geopolitical reasons. The term \"ISIL\" includes \"Levant,\" which refers to a broader geographic area that encompasses not just Iraq and Syria but also parts of Jordan, Lebanon, Israel, and Palestine. By using \"ISIL,\" Obama aimed to highlight the group's aspirations to expand beyond Syria and Iraq and to underscore the broader regional implications of their actions.\n\nAdditionally, some officials believe that using \"ISIL\" can help diminish the legitimacy the group seeks by framing itself as a state, as it emphasizes their ambition over the specific countries they currently control. This was part of a strategy to delegitimize the group's claim to authority and sovereignty. \n\nUltimately, the choice of terminology reflects a mixture of strategic, political, and nuanced considerations in the context of international relations and counter-terrorism efforts.",
